    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-12-24T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-12-24T16:00:00-05:00" n="867"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d867">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">864.01/12–2544: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-12-25T00:00:00+03:00"
                            >December 25, 1944—midnight.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received December 25—9:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4985. During a call this evening in connection with other matters Dekanozov told
                    me that Gromyko<note n="84" xml:id="d867fn84">Andrey Andreyevich Gromyko, Soviet
                        Ambassador in the United States.</note> had been instructed several days ago
                    to submit to the Department an <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi>
                    <note n="85" xml:id="d867fn85">See <hi rend="italic">infra.</hi>
                    </note> regarding the developments in Hungary leading up to the formation of the
                    Provisional <pb facs="0949" n="937" xml:id="pg_937"/> Government. He said
                    further that the Provisional Government had asked for an armistice. He explained
                    that when Mr. Molotov was well enough, which would be in a few days, he would
                    ask the British Chargé<note n="86" xml:id="d867fn86">John Balfour, British
                        Minister in the Soviet Union.</note> and myself to discuss the terms to be
                    offered.</p>
                <p>It would be helpful if I could be informed of the communications received by the
                    Department from the Soviet Embassy regarding Hungarian developments, the
                    attitude that the Department takes towards the new Provisional Government and
                    whether there are any changes in instructions previously given as to the
                    proposed armistice terms in the light of the new situation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
